Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
generateCapTbl(25.10)                                    generateCapTbl(25.10)

Name
       generateCapTbl  -  Reads  in  the interconnect technology (ICT) process
       file and generates a Capacitance table file

Syntax
        generateCapTbl

       [-help]

       [-cap <totalCapFactor>]

       [-encrypt]

       -output <fileName>

       [-res <resistanceFactor>]

       [-xcap <crossCouplingFactor>]

       [-lef <fileName> [-shrinkFactor <value>]]

       {-ict <fileName> | -incaptable <fileName>}

       Reads in the interconnect technology (ICT) process file and generates a
       Capacitance table file. The Capacitance table file  contains  a  header
       having  a summary of process information and manufacturing effects fol-
       lowed by tables containing coefficients used during RC extraction.

       The capacitance table is used both for preRoute extraction (above 32nm)
       and postRoute extraction -effortLevel low.

       Note: For TQuantus, IQuantus, preRoute extraction (32nm and below), and
       Standalone Quantus, a Quantus Techfile is needed instead of  a  Capaci-
       tance table.

       The  generateCapTbl command automatically omits the creation of coeffi-
       cients for the poly layers, local interconnect layers, and mimcap  lay-
       ers.   The   generateCapTbl  command  recognizes  poly  layers  by  the
       gate_forming_layer true statement.

       Note: The command accepts ICT files that contain the gate_forming_layer
       true construct in multiple conductor sections to allow handling of dif-
       fusion models as a conductor. In this case, the Innovus captable gener-
       ation process ignores all but the  last  gate_forming_layer  true  con-
       struct.  The  last  one is considered as poly and is used as the ground
       plate level for the metal layers above.

       The command does not support  grown_from_conformal  (non-planar  stack)
       construct defined in the ICT file.

       You can use the multi-CPU processing commands to generate a capacitance
       table  in the parallel mode. However, this functionality is only avail-
       able when invoking generateCapTbl from the  software  prompt,  and  not
       from the standalone utility generateCapTbl.

       To  generate  a  capacitance  table file in the parallel mode, you must
       first set up the multiple-CPU processing mode  using  the  multiple-CPU
       processing commands.

       See  the  following  multiple-CPU processing commands for more informa-
       tion:

              * setDistributeHost

              * setMultiCpuUsage

       For more information, see Distributed Processing in Extraction  in  the
       Innovus User Guide.

       Examples

              * To run the generateCapTbl command in the parallel mode on dif-
                ferent hosts, specify the following commands:

                setDistributeHost -rsh -add { host1 host2 host3 }

                setMultiCpuUsage -remoteHost 3

                generateCapTbl -ict sample.ict -output sample.capTbl

              * To  run the generateCapTbl command with three threads, specify
                the following commands:

                setDistributeHost -local

                setMultiCpuUsage -localCpu 3

                generateCapTbl -ict sample.ict -output sample.capTbl

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes type and  default  in-
              formation  for each generateCaptbl parameter. For a detailed de-
              scription of the command and all of its parameters, use the  man
              command:

               man generateCaptbl

       -cap <totalCapFactor>
              Specifies the capacitance scale factor. Use this parameter  with
              the  -incaptable  parameter to generate a capacitance table with
              capacitance values scaled by the specified scale factor.

       -encrypt
              Encrypts the generated capacitance table to protect the  process
              information  in  the  capacitance table header. When you use the
              create_rc_corner -cap_table command to read the encrypted capac-
              itance table, the software writes the version  number  that  was
              used  to  generate  the file, and the name of the process to the
              log file.

       -ict <fileName>
              Specifies the name and path to the ICT (interconnect technology)
              process file.

              To support multiple process corners, a capacitance table  should
              be created for each corner from the matching corner ICT file.

       -incaptable <fileName>
              Specifies  the  name  of  an existing capacitance table in ASCII
              format. You use this parameter along with the -encrypt parameter
              to create an encrypted version of an existing capacitance file.

              Note: The -ict and -incaptable parameters are mutualy exclusive.
              One of the two parameters must be specified.

       -lef <fileName>
              Specifies the name and the full path to the process LEF file for
              optimal accuracy. With the LEF file, this parameter generates  a
              capacitance  table  by using the actual wire widths as specified
              in the non-default rules defined in the LEF.  Without  the  LEF,
              the  software  uses generic widths and spacings, which might in-
              crease the need for interpolation during extraction.

       -output <fileName>
              Specifies the output filename that contains the capacitance  ta-
              ble. This is a required parameter.

       -res <resistanceFactor>
              Specifies  the  resistance scale factor. Use this parameter with
              the -incaptable parameter to generate a capacitance  table  with
              resistance values scaled by the specified scale factor.

       -shrinkFactor <value>
              Specifies  the  value  by which the measurements in the optional
              LEF file have to be shrunk for the technology used with this de-
              sign. Use this parameter only with the -lef parameter  and  when
              the  LEF  technology does not match the target technology in the
              ICT file. Innovus scales the dimensions  when  reading  the  LEF
              file  using  the shrinkFactor specified. The ICT file should al-
              ways refer to the target technology (min width and min spacing).

              Note: When working on a design that needs to be scaled  down  in
              Innovus,  you  must  also set the shrinkfactor in Design Import.
              This tells the extractor to scale  down  all  geometries  before
              processing.

              When  the ICT file contains a layout_scale in the process decla-
              ration part, you do not need to specify the  shrink  factor.  In
              this  case,  the  embedded shrink factor will also be written in
              the captable header. Also, there is then  no  need  to  set  the
              shrink  factor  in  the  Design  Import  form. The embedded lay-
              out_scale is used to support half nodes such as 40nm technology.

              Default: 1.0

       -xcap <crossCouplingFactor>
              Specifies the cross-coupling capacitance scale factor. Use  this
              parameter  with  the -incaptable parameter to generate a capaci-
              tance table with cross-coupling capacitance values scaled by the
              specified scale factor.

Example
       The following command reads in the ICT file test.ict, and  generates  a
       new.capTbl output file:

       generateCapTbl -ict test.ict -output new.CapTbl

